Elbow plot of Principal Components:
The elbow plot revealed a steep decline in standard deviation from PC1 through PC4, capturing the major sources of transcriptional variation including myeloid versus fibroblast (PC1), epithelial versus myeloid (PC2), and macrophage versus neutrophil (PC5) cell type differences. The curve plateaued at approximately PC15, beyond which additional components explained minimal additional variance. Consequently, the first 15 principal components were selected for downstream clustering and UMAP embedding, balancing biological information capture with noise reduction.

Heatmap of Principal Components:
The Heatmap for PC1 revealed a clear biological axis separating myeloid and fibroblast cell populations across 500 cells. PC1-negative cells showed high expression of myeloid markers including Tyrobp, Fcer1g, C1qb, Aif1, and MHC-II genes (H2-Aa, H2-Ab1), while PC1-positive cells showed high expression of fibroblast and stromal markers including Sparc, Col1a2, Col3a1, and Dcn. This distinct separation confirms that PC1 captures a biologically meaningful axis of variation between immune and stromal cell populations in the nasal mucosa, supporting its inclusion in downstream clustering and UMAP embedding.

PCA plot:
PCA of the 156,572 cells across all five timepoints revealed three broad regions of transcriptional variation in PC1-PC2 space. A dense cluster in the positive PC1 region likely represents the abundant epithelial and neuronal populations, while a diffuse central cloud corresponds to heterogeneous immune cell populations. An elongated tail extending into negative PC1 space, consistent with the fibroblast and stromal cell loadings identified in PC1, represents transcriptionally distinct stromal populations. Cells from all five timepoints were distributed throughout all regions of PCA space confirming the absence of timepoint-specific batch effects and supporting the comparability of samples for downstream analysis.
